# WESAD Stress Detection System 🧠
 
A subject-independent stress classification system trained on the WESAD dataset. Uses chest-worn biosignal data — electrodermal activity, skin temperature, and respiration — to classify a person's physiological state into four categories: Baseline, Stress, Amusement, and Meditation.
 
**Best model accuracy: 71.52%** — achieved with an ExtraTrees ensemble of 1500 trees using Quantile-Normal transformation for subject-independent generalization.
 
---
 
## The Problem
 
Stress detection from physiological signals is hard because every person's body is different. A "stressed" reading for one person might be their baseline for another. Most models fail when tested on subjects they've never seen.
 
This project solves that with **Quantile-Normal Transformation** — a normalization technique that maps each subject's raw biosignals into a standard normal distribution before feature extraction, effectively removing individual biological baselines and making the model generalize across subjects it was never trained on.
 
---
 
## Dataset
 
**WESAD** (Wearable Stress and Affect Detection) — a publicly available multimodal dataset for stress and affect recognition.
 
- 15 subjects (S2–S17, excluding S12)
- Chest-worn RespiBAN sensor
- Signals used: EDA (700Hz), Temperature (700Hz), Respiration (700Hz)
- 4 labels: 1 = Baseline, 2 = Stress, 3 = Amusement, 4 = Meditation
> Dataset not included in this repository. Download from: https://uni-siegen.de/life/forschung/telekom_stiftung/ubisys/tools/wesad.html
 
---
 
## What It Does
 
- Loads raw WESAD `.pkl` files per subject
- Applies **Quantile-Normal Transformation** per subject to eliminate individual biological baseline differences
- Extracts 30 statistical features per window (10 stats × 3 signals): mean, std, variance, min, max, median, 25th percentile, 75th percentile, skewness, kurtosis
- Uses sliding windows of 10 seconds (7000 samples @ 700Hz) with 50% overlap
- Trains an **ExtraTrees Ensemble** with SMOTE-Tomek class balancing
- Evaluates on held-out subjects (S6–S9) — fully subject-independent validation
---
 
## Model Comparison
 
Three model configurations were trained and evaluated:
 
| Model | Trees | Max Depth | Features | Class Weight | Test Accuracy |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Model 1 | 1200 | 40 | sqrt | balanced | 70.98% |
| Model 2 | 2000 | 50 | all (30) | balanced_subsample | 70.10% |
| **Model 3 ✅** | **1500** | **45** | **log2** | **balanced** | **71.52%** |
 
**Model 3 selected** — best generalization across unseen subjects.
 
